egory:La Liga managers]]\n[[Category:Russian Premier League managers]]\n[[Category:Premier League managers]]\n[[Category:Qatar Stars League managers]]\n[[Category:Danish expatriate football managers]]\n[[Category:Danish expatriate sportspeople in Russia]]\n[[Category:Danish expatriate sportspeople in Wales]]\n[[Category:Danish expatriate sportspeople in Qatar]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Russia]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Wales]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Qatar]]\n[[Category:Danish knights]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Michael Laudrup\n| image = Michael Laudrup 2016c.jpg\n| image_size = 240\n| caption = Laudrup in 2016\n| fullname = Michael Laudrup<ref>{{cite book |last=Gaarskj\u00e6r |first=Jesper |title=Bar\u00e7a: Historien om FC Barcelona |year=2010 |publisher=Gyldendal |location=Sheffield |isbn=978-87-02-08764-2 |page=135}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1964|6|15|df=y}}<ref name=BDFutbol>{{cite web |url=http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/l/l1966.html |title=Laudrup: Michael Laudrup: Manager |publisher=BDFutbol |accessdate=21 December 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Frederiksberg]], Denmark\n| height = 1.83 m<ref name=BDFutbol/>\n| position = [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|Attacking midfielder]], [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| currentclub = \n| youthyears1 = 1971\u20131973\n| youthclubs1 = [[Vanl\u00f8se IF|Vanl\u00f8se]]\n| youthyears2 = 1973\u20131976\n| youthclubs2 = [[Br\u00f8ndby IF|Br\u00f8ndby]]\n| youthyears3 = 1977\u20131981\n| youthclubs3 = [[Kj\u00f8benhavns Boldklub|KB]]\n| years1 = 1981\u20131982\n| clubs1 = [[Kj\u00f8benhavns Boldklub|KB]]\n| caps1 = 14\n| goals1 = 3\n| years2 = 1982\u20131983\n| clubs2 = [[Br\u00f8ndby IF|Br\u00f8ndby]]\n| caps2 = 38\n| goals2 = 24\n| years3 = 1983\u20131985\n| clubs3 = [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]]\n| caps3 = 60\n| goals3 = 9\n| years4 = 1985\u20131989\n| clubs4 = [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]]\n| caps4 = 102\n| goals4 = 16\n| years5 = 1989\u20131994\n| clubs5 = [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]\n| caps5 = 167\n| goals5 = 40\n| years6 = 1994\u20131996\n| clubs6 = [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]]\n| caps6 = 62\n| goals6 = 12\n| years7 = 1996\u20131997\n| clubs7 = [[Vissel Kobe]]\n| caps7 = 15\n| goals7 = 6\n| years8 = 1997\u20131998\n| clubs8 = [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]]\n| caps8 = 21\n| goals8 = 11\n| totalcaps = 479\n| totalgoals = 121\n| nationalyears1 = 1980\n| nationalteam1 = [[Denmark national under-17 football team|Denmark U17]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 4\n| nationalgoals1 = 2\n| nationalyears2 = 1980\u20131981\n| nationalteam2 = [[Denmark national under-19 football team|Denmark U19]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 19\n| nationalgoals2 = 12\n| nationalyears3 = 1982\n| nationalteam3 = [[Denmark national under-21 football team|Denmark U21]]\n| nationalcaps3 = 2\n| nationalgoals3 = 0\n| nationalyears4 = 1982\u20131998\n| nationalteam4 = [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]]\n| nationalcaps4 = 104\n| nationalgoals4 = 37\n| manageryears1 = 2000\u20132002\n| manageryears2 = 2002\u20132006\n| manageryears3 = 2007\u20132008\n| manageryears4 = 2008\u20132009\n| manageryears5 = 2010\u20132011\n| manageryears6 = 2012\u20132014\n| manageryears7 = 2014\u20132015\n| manageryears8 = 2016\u20132018\n| managerclubs1 = [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] (assistant manager)\n| managerclubs2 = [[Br\u00f8ndby IF|Br\u00f8ndby]]\n| managerclubs3 = [[Getafe CF|Getafe]]\n| managerclubs4 = [[FC Spartak Moscow|Spartak Moscow]]\n| managerclubs5 = [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]]\n| managerclubs6 = [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]]\n| managerclubs7 = [[Lekhwiya SC|Lekhwiya]]\n| managerclubs8 = [[Al-Rayyan SC|Al Rayyan]]\n| medaltemplates = {{Medal|Sport|Men's [[Association football|football]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{fb|DEN}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIFA Confederations Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|W|[[1995 FIFA Confederations Cup|1995 Saudi Arabia]]|}}\n}}\n\n'''Michael Laudrup''' ({{IPA-da|\u02c8mi\u02cck\u02b0\u00e6\u02c0l \u02c8law\u02c0t\u0281\u0254p}}, born 15 June 1964) is a Danish professional [[Association football|football]] coach and former player. He is regarded as one of the greatest players of his generation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/nov/21/michael-laudrup-portrait-of-an-icon-denmark-barcelona-real-madrid |title=Michael Laudrup: a portrait of an icon |publisher=[[The Guardian]] |date=21 November 2017 |accessdate=17 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/8342725.stm |title=Swapping Barca for the Bernabeu |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=27 November 2009 |accessdate=17 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/watch/video/sports/football/9636977/footballs-greatest-michael-laudrup |title=Football's Greatest \u2013 Michael Laudrup |publisher=Sky Sports |accessdate=17 May 2018}}</ref> He is the older brother of fellow retired footballer [[Brian Laudrup]].\n\nDuring his playing career, Laudrup won league titles with [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]], [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]], [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] and [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]], playing mainly as an [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|attacking midfielder]], although he was also capable of playing in other offensive positions. A world class [[playmaker]], he was a member of [[Johan Cruyff]]'s \"[[FC Barcelona#Dream Team|Dream Team]]\" at Barcelona, where he won nine trophies, including four successive [[La Liga]] titles from 1991 to 1994 and the [[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]] in [[1992 European Cup Final|1992]]. Laudrup moved to [[El Cl\u00e1sico|arch-rivals]] Real Madrid in 1994, with whom he won his fifth La Liga title in a row.\n\nLaudrup made his debut for the [[Denmark national football team|Denmark national team]] on his 18th birthday in 1982, and scored 37 goals in 104 appearances. He starred in the [[1986 FIFA World Cup]], and from November 1994, he captained Denmark for a total of 28 matches,<ref>Michael Laudrup started his last 27 matches as captain, while he had taken over the armband in the 1 June 1994 1\u20132 loss to [[Norway national football team|Norway]], when then captain [[Lars Olsen]] was substituted.</ref> including the victorious [[1995 King Fahd Cup|1995 Confederations Cup]] tournament. He played alongside his brother Brian in the Denmark team that reached the quarter-finals of the [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998 World Cup]], and retired as an active player after the tournament.\n\nIn 1999, Laudrup was voted the Best Foreign Player in Spanish Football over the preceding 25-year period<ref>IFHOC, [http://www.hallofchampions.com/gala/index.html The Gala in Barcelona], 1 February 1999</ref> and in April 2000 he was knighted, receiving the [[Order of the Dannebrog]]. In November 2003, to celebrate [[UEFA]]'s Jubilee, he was selected as the [[UEFA Jubilee Awards|Golden Player]] of Denmark by the [[Danish Football Association]], their most outstanding player of the past 50 years.<ref name=jubilee1>UEFA.com, [http://www.uefa.com/uefa/news/Kind=256/newsId=130150.html Golden Players take center stage] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040312203128/http://www.uefa.com/uefa/news/Kind%3D256/newsId%3D130150.html |date=12 March 2004 }}, 29 November 2003.</ref> He was officially named the best Danish footballer of all time by the Danish Football Association (DBU) in November 2006.<ref>[http://www.dbu.dk/news/newsShow.aspx?id=235647 Michael Laudrup bedste spiller gennem tiderne], ''DBU.dk'', 13 November 2006</ref> He was named by [[Pel\u00e9]] in the [[FIFA 100]] list of the world's greatest living players at a [[FIFA]] awards ceremony in 2004.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/3533891.stm |title=Pele's list of the greatest |publisher=BBC Sport |date=4 March 2004 |accessdate=22 November 2013 }}</ref> In April 2013, he was named by ''[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]'' in the \"Best foreign eleven in [[History of Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid's history]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2013/04/11/en/football/real_madrid/1365709938.html|title=The best foreign eleven in Real Madrid's history|date=12 April 2013|work=Marca|location=Spain}}</ref> He is by some considered the greatest Scandinavian footballer ever, ahead of the likes of [[Zlatan Ibrahimovi\u0107]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Laudrup named best Nordic footballer ever|url = http://www.thelocal.dk/20150609/laudrup-named-best-nordic-footballer-ever|website = thelocal.dk|accessdate = 20 November 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"BT Sport\"/>\n\nAfter retiring as a player, Laudrup took up coaching, and became assistant manager of the Denmark national team. He got his first manager job at former club [[Br\u00f8ndby IF|Br\u00f8ndby]] in 2002, whom he guided to the 2005 [[Danish Superliga]] championship. He chose not to extend his contract with Br\u00f8ndby in May 2006. He took over as coach of [[Getafe CF|Getafe]] and had notable success there. He brought the club comparative success in the [[Copa del Rey]] and [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]], and the team's attacking style received plaudits. On 15 June 2012, Laudrup was appointed the manager of [[Premier League]] club [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]] on a two-year contract.<ref>Clutton, Graham (15 June 2012) [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/swansea-city/9333566/Michael-Laudrup-appointed-new-Swansea-City-manager.html Laudrup appointed Swansea City manager]. ''The Daily Telegraph''. Retrieved 18 April 2015.</ref> In his first season in south Wales, he won the [[EFL Cup|League Cup]], the first major English trophy in Swansea's 100-year history. On 4 February 2014, he was sacked by Swansea after a \"significant\" slump in the Premier League, leaving them two points above the relegation zone.<ref name=\"BBC Sport\">{{cite news|title=Swansea sack Michael Laudrup and place Garry Monk in charge |url = https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/26042067 |publisher=BBC Sport|date=4 February 2014|accessdate=4 February 2014}}</ref> Laudrup then managed [[Qatar]]i clubs [[Al-Duhail SC|Lekhwiya]] and [[Al-Rayyan SC|Al Rayyan]] between 2014 and 2018.\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Frederiksberg]], Copenhagen,<ref name=BDFutbol/> Michael Laudrup began playing football in father [[Finn Laudrup]]'s childhood club [[Vanl\u00f8se IF|Vanl\u00f8se]]. When Finn Laudrup became player/coach of [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] in 1973, the family moved to [[Br\u00f8ndby]] and both Michael and his brother [[Brian Laudrup]] started playing for the club as well. Michael followed his father to the top-flight [[Danish 1st Division]] club [[K\u00f8benhavns Boldklub]] in 1976, while Brian remained at Br\u00f8ndby.\n\n===Early career===\nLaudrup made his senior debut playing for KB ([[Kj\u00f8benhavns Boldklub]]) in 1981, and made his debut for the Danish under-19 national team in February 1981.<ref>{{in lang|da}} [http://home6.inet.tele.dk/pin/landsholdet/Laudrup_Michael.htm Laudrup, Michael] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070331041420/http://home6.inet.tele.dk/pin/landsholdet/Laudrup_Michael.htm |date=31 March 2007 }} at ''Peders Fodboldstatistik''</ref> In all, he scored a combined total of 14 goals in 25 games at various youth levels. He went back to play for Br\u00f8ndby in 1982, where his father had ended his career in 1981, contributing to the [[promotion and relegation|promotion]] of Br\u00f8ndby to the 1st Division.\n\nAt Br\u00f8ndby, Laudrup scored two goals in the club's 1st Division debut game, as fellow promoted team [[Boldklubben 1909]] were beaten 7\u20131. He scored 15 league goals in 1982, and ended the season as the third top goal scorer of the 1st Division. His accomplishments earned him the 1982 [[Danish Player of the Year]] award. He played part of the 1983 season for Br\u00f8ndby, and scored nine goals, before he was sold to defending [[Serie A]] champions [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] from Italy in June 1983. It was the biggest [[transfer deal]] in Danish football at the time, worth around $1&nbsp;million. He was due to sign for [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] the same year on a three-year contract, but at the last minute, Liverpool proposed a four-year contract and Laudrup opted not to sign.<ref>[[#Kvist|Kvist]] (2001), p. 36</ref>\n\nUnder restriction of a maximum of two foreign players in the team, of which the club had Polish midfielder [[Zbigniew Boniek]] and [[Michel Platini]], Juventus initially lent Laudrup to newly promoted [[Rome]] club [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]] for a single season, something he had not been informed about before signing for Juventus. With Lazio, he scored two goals in his Serie A debut, a 2\u20134 loss to [[Hellas Verona F.C.|Hellas Verona]]. In his first year at Lazio, Lazio narrowly avoided [[relegation]], but as Juventus wanted to keep Boniek and Platini, he stayed for another year. Lazio started the [[1984\u201385 Serie A|1984\u201385 season]] poorly, eventually finishing in last place to become relegated to [[Serie B]]. Laudrup scored just one goal that season.\n\nLaudrup returned to Juventus in summer 1985 to replace Zbigniew Boniek, playing alongside Michel Platini. In his first year at the club, he won the [[1985\u201386 Serie A]] as well as the [[Intercontinental Cup (football)|Intercontinental Cup]] trophy, scoring the equalising goal in the final of the latter tournament, although he later missed a penalty in the resulting shoot-out;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.juventus.com/en/club/torphy-room/intercontinental-cup/coppa-intercontinentale-1985.php|title=Intercontinental Cup 1985|publisher=juventus.com|accessdate=20 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2015/dec/18/michel-platini-uefa-fifa-juventus|title=Michel Platini's playing brilliance can be seen through the murk|work=The Guardian|author1=Richard Williams|date=18 December 2015|accessdate=20 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myjuve.it/season-1985-juventus/intercontinental_cup-juventus-argentinos_juniors-2-2-2617.aspx|title=Intercontinental Cup 1985|publisher=myjuve.it|accessdate=20 October 2017}}</ref> he was once again named Danish Player of the Year in 1985. However, the following season was no success for Laudrup, who suffered multiple injuries, much like the majority of Juventus players, including Platini. When Platini retired in 1987, Laudrup was expected to lead the team in his place, playing alongside newly bought Welsh forward [[Ian Rush]]. But Laudrup failed to live up to Platini's standards and did not score any goals, despite playing all 30 matches of the [[1987\u201388 Serie A|1987\u201388 season]].\n\n===Barcelona===\nAfter an unsuccessful season with Juventus, Laudrup decided it was time to leave, looking for a new experience after six years in Italy. In 1989, he joined Spanish club [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] on the premise that Netherlands legend [[Johan Cruyff]], his childhood role model, had been assembling a team that was striving for success. Immediately, Laudrup enjoyed major success under Cruyff's leadership, citing the Dutchman's philosophy and perception of the game as one of the main assets that helped foster his talent. He was one of the restricted three foreign players allowed in the team, alongside Dutch defender [[Ronald Koeman]] and Bulgarian striker [[Hristo Stoichkov]], who were the pillars of the ''Bar\u00e7a'' \"[[FC Barcelona#Dream Team|Dream Team]]\", along with rising stars [[Pep Guardiola]], [[Jos\u00e9 Mari Bakero]], and [[Txiki Begiristain]].\n\nThe Dream Team played attractive football that was comparable to the 1970s [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]] team, and won four consecutive [[La Liga]] championships from 1991 to 1994, as well as the [[1991\u201392 European Cup]], along with the [[1992 UEFA Super Cup]], [[1989\u201390 Copa del Rey]] and [[1991 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a|1991]] and [[1992 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a|1992]] [[Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a]] titles. Laudrup was twice named the best player of the year in Spain during his Barcelona years. When ''Bar\u00e7a'' hired a fourth foreign star player, Brazilian striker [[Rom\u00e1rio]] in 1993, it meant the four foreigners would rotate as the three foreign players allowed in each match, and when he was not selected for the 1994 European Cup final 0\u20134 loss to [[A.C. Milan|Milan]] (amid conflicts with Cruyff), his time at Barcelona was effectively over.<ref name=\"theguardian.com\">[https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/nov/21/michael-laudrup-portrait-of-an-icon-denmark-barcelona-real-madrid]</ref>\n\nLaudrup's departure from Barcelona was a huge blow for the fans and his teammates alike. Pep Guardiola was reportedly so upset by the news that he cried and begged Laudrup to change his mind.<ref name=\"theguardian.com\"/> Reflecting on his time at Barcelona, Laudrup commented, \"I think we played some very good football, and I think most of all we demonstrated that even without getting the ten best players in the world, you can have the best team. Because everybody talked about Begiristain, Bakero, Guardiola, Stoichkov, and Koeman, but when we started none of us was a best player, then we became maybe the best team in the world, together with AC Milan in that period.\"<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">Sky Sports Special&nbsp;\u2013 Football's Greatest: Michael Laudrup.</ref>\n\n===Real Madrid===\nIn 1994, Laudrup completed a controversial move from ''Bar\u00e7a'' to [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] after he fell-out with Johan Cruyff. On this, Laudrup stated he did not have a hidden agenda. It was the year before the [[1994 FIFA World Cup]] and according to him, because players usually suffer a drop in performance after such a major international tournament, he correctly predicted that Barcelona would not win major trophies the following season.\n\nDespite widespread belief Laudrup joined arch-rivals Real Madrid in an attempt to \"get back\" at Cruyff, the decision was based on the fact Real Madrid had been struggling for a long period and were eager to return to supremacy, like Barcelona when he decided to join them. Laudrup said, \"People say I wanted to go to Real Madrid just to get revenge. I say revenge from what? I've had a perfect time; five fantastic years here [at Barcelona]. I went to Madrid because they were so hungry to win, and they had four or five players who went to the World Cup. I said this would be perfect; new coach, new players, and hungry to win.\"<ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/>\n\nLaudrup went on to guide Real Madrid in a championship-winning season that would end the ''Bar\u00e7a'' stranglehold, making him the only player ever to win the Spanish league five times in a row playing for two different clubs. After the initial success at Real, a lacklustre season would be in store for the club. Despite only playing two seasons at Real Madrid, he was voted the 12th-best player in Real Madrid history in an internet survey by Spanish newspaper ''[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]'' when the club celebrated its 100th anniversary in 2002.<ref>{{in lang|da}} Palle \"Banks\" J\u00f8rgensen, \"''Landsholdenes 2198 profiler''\", Danmark, 2004, {{ISBN|87-89564-04-9}}, p. 214</ref> While playing with Barcelona, he participated in the 5\u20130 victory over rivals Real Madrid in the 1993\u201394 season. The following season while playing for Real Madrid, he aided in the revenge beating Madrid gave ''Bar\u00e7a'', the final score also ending 5\u20130. [[Daniel Storey]] wrote of Laudrup,  \"no other player is loved on both sides of the cl\u00e1sico divide quite like Laudrup\" as he remains held in high regard by both Bar\u00e7a and Madrid fans.<ref name=\"theguardian.com\"/>\n\n===Later career and retirement===\nIn 1996, Laudrup left Real Madrid to play for [[Vissel Kobe]] in Japan, helping them to promotion from the [[Japan Football League (1992\u20131998)|second-tier Japan Football League]] to the [[J1 League]]. He was registered as a player in [[Premier League of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnian Premier League]] club [[NK \u010celik Zenica|\u010celik Zenica]] in a controversial signing in which he did not play any games for \u010celik, but was signed as a player.<ref>[http://www.fyens.dk/article/90102:Sport--Laudrup-var-registreret-i-bosnisk-klub-SNYD--Det-hollandske-skattevaesen-foeler-sig-snydt-i-forbindelse-med-Michael-Laudrups-skifte-til-Ajax Laudrup var registreret i bosnisk klub SNYD: Det hollandske skattev\u0107sen f\u0159ler sig snydt i forbindelse med Michael Laudrups skifte til Ajax&nbsp;\u2013 fyens.dk&nbsp;\u2013 Sport] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921060142/http://www.fyens.dk/article/90102:Sport--Laudrup-var-registreret-i-bosnisk-klub-SNYD--Det-hollandske-skattevaesen-foeler-sig-snydt-i-forbindelse-med-Michael-Laudrups-skifte-til-Ajax |date=21 September 2013 }}. fyens.dk. 23 October 2004.</ref> After the details were resolved, he ended his playing career in a championship winning season at Dutch side Ajax in 1998.\n\nFollowing his retirement, Laudrup sometimes turned out to play for [[Lyngby Boldklub|Lyngby]]'s Old Boys team in his spare time.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120320215520/http://lyngby-boldklub.dk/Nyheder/Seneste_nyt/Trupperne_til_Oldboys_Landspokalfinalen/ Trupperne til Oldboys Landspokalfinalen]. lyngby-boldklub.dk. 13 October 2005</ref>\n\n==International career==\nLaudrup was called up for the [[Denmark national football team|Denmark national team]] during Br\u00f8ndby's debut season in the top-flight. On his 18th birthday on 15 June 1982, he became the then-second-youngest Danish national team player ever, following [[Harald Nielsen]]. Despite playing for relegation battlers Lazio, Laudrup starred for the Denmark national team at [[UEFA Euro 1984]], playing all four of Denmark's matches.\n\nLaudrup participated in the [[1986 FIFA World Cup]] in Mexico, a performance which is best remembered for his exceptional solo dribble and goal in the 6\u20131 defeat of [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]]. He was also a part of the disappointing Denmark squad at [[UEFA Euro 1988|Euro 1988]], though Laudrup experienced personal success, scoring one of Denmark's two goals.\n\nFollowing three matches in the qualification campaign for [[UEFA Euro 1992|Euro 1992]], Laudrup opted to quit the national team in November 1990 (alongside his brother Brian Laudrup and [[Jan M\u00f8lby]]) following differences with coach [[Richard M\u00f8ller Nielsen]].<ref>\"Historien om Michael Laudrups farvel\", ''[[Politiken]]'', 26 November 1990, Section:Sport, p.2</ref> The Danes originally failed to qualify but were later given [[Yugoslavia national football team|Yugoslavia]]'s place as Yugoslavia were kicked out due to [[Yugoslav Wars|war in their country]]. Notwithstanding their qualification, Laudrup rated Denmark's chances of success so low he stayed on holiday, a decision he must have regretted as Denmark beat holders [[Netherlands national football team|the Netherlands]] on penalties in the semi-finals with legendary keeper [[Peter Schmeichel]] surprisingly saving a [[Marco van Basten]] penalty in the shoot-out. In the [[UEFA Euro 1992 Final|final]] against world champions and favourites [[Germany national football team|Germany]], the Danes stunned the world with a 2\u20130 win thanks to goals from [[John Jensen]] and [[Kim Vilfort]], making it arguably the biggest surprise in a [[UEFA European Championship]] final.\n\nLaudrup returned to Nielsen's Danish squad in August 1993, but saw [[Spain national football team|Spain]] and the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]] qualify for the [[1994 FIFA World Cup|1994 World Cup]] ahead of Denmark. He scored a goal in the 2\u20130 victory against [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]], as Denmark won the [[1995 King Fahd Cup|1995 Intercontinental Cup]]. He also scored four goals in ten matches as Denmark qualified for [[UEFA Euro 1996|Euro 1996]], though the tournament would leave no positives for him.\n\nLaudrup's last matches for Denmark came at the [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998 World Cup]], when he captained the nation to the quarter-final. Laudrup made his [[List of footballers with 100 or more caps|100th appearance]] for Denmark in the team's opening game of the tournament, a 1\u20130 defeat of [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]] in [[Lens, Pas-de-Calais|Lens]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1998-06-14/sports/9806130177_1_michael-laudrup-world-cup-marc-rieper|title=Laudrup Celebrates Centennial Cap|date=14 June 1998|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Denmark was defeated 2\u20133 by [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] in the quarter-finals, and both Michael and Brian Laudrup announced their international retirement following the elimination. Both brothers ended their international careers on a high note as both Michael and Brian were named in FIFA's [[1998 FIFA World Cup#All-star team|All-Star Team]].\n\n==Style of play==\n[[File:Michael Laudrup 2015b.jpg|thumb|Laudrup demonstrating his skills in Qatar, 2015]]\n\nA quick, intelligent and talented [[midfielder]], known for his pace on the ball, Laudrup is regarded as one of the most effective and versatile [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|attacking midfielders]], as well as one of the most skilful and elegant players in the history of the game. Although primarily an offensive [[playmaker]], he was capable of playing in several positions in or behind the front-line, and was even deployed as a [[Forward (association football)#Winger|winger]], as a [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|central midfielder]] or [[Midfielder#Deep-lying playmaker|deep-lying playmaker]], or as a [[Forward (association football)#Second striker|second striker]] on occasion, in particular in his youth. Laudrup is considered by many in the sport as one of the best passers of all time, and as one of the most technically accomplished players ever.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ilpalloneracconta.blogspot.ca/2008/06/quando-arriva-alla-lazio-michelino-gi.html|title=Michael LAUDRUP|publisher=Il Pallone Racconta|language=Italian|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Michael Laudrup\">{{cite web|url=https://www.fcbarcelona.com/club/history/card/michael-laudrup|title=Michael Laudrup|publisher=FC Barcelona|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportmediaset.mediaset.it/calcio/calcio/articoli/71652/i-piu-grandi-numeri-11-della-storia.shtml|title=I pi\u00f9 grandi numeri 11 della storia|publisher=Sport Mediaset|language=Italian|author1=MASSIMILIANO CRISTINA|date=11 November 2011|accessdate=14 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/18426736.app|title=Jan Molby backs Michael Laudrup for Swansea City manager job|publisher=BBC|date=13 June 2012|accessdate=14 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"tuttojuve.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tuttojuve.com/gli-eroi-bianconeri/gli-eroi-in-bianconero-michael-laudrup-193006|title=Gli eroi in bianconero: Michael LAUDRUP|publisher=tuttojuve.com|language=Italian|author=Stefano Bedeschi|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://it.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=1924706.html|title=La vittoria pi\u00f9 bella di Laudrup|publisher=UEFA|language=Italian|date=25 February 2013|accessdate=11 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/1634018-25-most-skilled-passers-in-world-football-history |title=25 Most Skilled Passers in World Football History |publisher=bleacherreport.com |author1=Max Towle |date=9 May 2013 |accessdate=10 October 2018 }}</ref> He was ranked among the best players in Europe, with the French three time [[European footballer of the year]] award winner [[Michel Platini]] describing him as one of the most talented players ever, only lamenting his lack of selfishness causing him to score too few goals.<ref name=\"jubilee\">Frits Ahlstr\u00f8m, [http://www.uefa.com/uefa/history/associationweeks/association=35/newsId=145557.html Laudrup is greatest Dane], [[UEFA]], 29 March 2004</ref> Despite being primarily a creative team player, he also possessed an accurate shot.<ref name=\"Michael Laudrup\"/><ref name=\"tuttojuve.com\"/>\n\nIn a 2006 interview, Laudrup's Real Madrid teammate [[Ra\u00fal (footballer)|Ra\u00fal]] called him the best player he had ever played with.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">\"Konges\u00f8nnens b\u00f8n: Kom til Madrid\", ''[[Ekstra Bladet]]'', 16 April 2006</ref> His Barcelona teammate Rom\u00e1rio said the same, opining he was able to create and score goals almost at will, and ranked him the fifth-best player in the history of the game (behind Pel\u00e9, [[Diego Maradona]], himself and [[Zinedine Zidane]]).<ref name=\"Romarios efterm\u00e6le\">{{cite news|work=[[Jyllands-Posten]]|date=8 March 2008|accessdate=8 March 2008|url=http://jp.dk/arkiv/?id=379867&eceExpr=Romarios%20efterm%E6le&eceArchive=o |title=Romarios efterm\u00e6le}}</ref> In addition to his playing ability, Laudrup was known for his good conduct on the pitch and he never received a [[Misconduct (association football)|red card]] in his career.\n\nNicknamed \"The Prince of Denmark,\"<ref name=fourfourtwo.com/><ref name=storiedicalcio/> throughout his career, Laudrup was acclaimed for his technique, balance, elegance, ball control, and [[Dribbling#Association football|dribbling]] ability, as well as his vision, ability to read the game, and range of passing, including deep passes, through balls, and [[Cross (football)|crosses]], which made him an excellent assist provider.<ref name=treccani.it>{{cite web|url=http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/michael-e-brian-laudrup_%28Enciclopedia_dello_Sport%29/|title=LAUDRUP, Michael e Brian|publisher=Treccani: Enciclopedia dello Sport (2002)|language=Italian|author1=Salvatore Lo Presti|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fcbarcelona.com/en/news/1141715/legendary-laudrup |title=Legendary Laudrup |publisher=FC Barcelona |date=3 April 2013 |accessdate=14 December 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"Icon\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/nov/21/michael-laudrup-portrait-of-an-icon-denmark-barcelona-real-madrid |title=Michael Laudrup: a portrait of an icon |work=The Guardian |last1=Storey |first1=Daniel |date=21 November 2017 |accessdate=14 December 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"RMCF Profile\">{{cite web |url=https://www.realmadrid.com/en/about-real-madrid/history/football-legends/michael-laudrup |title=The King of the final ball |publisher=Real Madrid |accessdate=14 December 2019}}</ref> In regard to his vision, [[Jorge Valdano]], the Argentinian coach of Laudrup in Real Madrid, said, \"[H]e has eyes everywhere.\" His trademark move&nbsp;\u2013 looking one way and passing the other&nbsp;\u2013 fooled countless opponents during his career.<ref name=fourfourtwo.com>{{cite web|url=http://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/my-perfect-10-michael-laudrup#:Fh0YjQZK9l2G2A|title=My Perfect 10: Michael Laudrup|publisher=FourFourTwo|author1=Jamie Bowman|date=3 September 2010|accessdate=14 March 2016}}</ref> The Laudrup dribble, a signature feint also known as the ''croqueta'', was perhaps the best-known part of his game, and involved him quickly moving the ball from one foot to the other away from the defender, a move which was later also popularised by later Barcelona midfielder [[Andr\u00e9s Iniesta]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.marca.com/en/football/international-football/2017/01/16/587cba1046163fdd518b4612.html |title=The best 'croquetas' in world football |newspaper=Marca |date=16 January 2017 |accessdate=3 August 2018 }}</ref> Laudrup's ball skills and [[Dummy (football)|feints]] were combined with creativity, which he used to get past defenders in one on one situations.<ref name=storiedicalcio/> This led to the expression \"Made in Laudrup\", widely used in Spain about his creative style of play. Numerous teammates of his have said, \"Just run, he will always find a way of passing you the ball.\"\n\nIn Barcelona, Laudrup played alongside Hristo Stoichkov, who scored many goals from Laudrup's passes, like [[Iv\u00e1n Zamorano]] (who called Laudrup \"''El Genio''\" [\"The Genius\"]) during Laudrup's time at Real Madrid. Zamorano was going through a hard spell in Madrid, but when Laudrup arrived to assist his goals, Zamorano immediately became ''pichichi'', the top goalscorer of La Liga.<ref name=fourfourtwo.com/> Throughout his career, his number of assists were almost always the highest of his team. Despite his reputation as one of the most technically gifted and creative players of his generation, certain players, pundits and managers have questioned Laudrup's work rate and consistency throughout his career at times.<ref name=\"tuttojuve.com\"/><ref name=storiedicalcio>{{cite web|url=http://www.storiedicalcio.altervista.org/michael-laudrup.html|title=Michael Laudrup: Il Principe di Danimarca|publisher=Storie di Calcio|language=Italian|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=fourfourtwo.com/> His former Juventus teammate and admirer Michel Platini, for example, even once said, \"[Laudrup]'s the greatest player in the world, in training.\"<ref name=storiedicalcio/><ref name=treccani.it/>\n\n==Managerial career==\n[[File:Michael-laudrup-2000.jpg|thumb|right|Laudrup during his time as assistant manager of Denmark in 2000]]\n\n===Early years===\nAfter his playing career ended with Ajax, Laudrup became a coach at age 36 when he started serving as an assistant coach for the Denmark national team head coach [[Morten Olsen]] in 2000. The national team would play a [[4-2-3-1|4\u20132\u20133\u20131 formation]], depending on two fast [[winger (football)|wingers]] and with the aim to dominate games with a short-passing possession game. Together, they led Denmark to the knock-out stage of the [[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002 World Cup]].\n\n===Br\u00f8ndby===\nAfter his success as Denmark assistant manager, Laudrup signed on as manager for [[Danish Superliga]] club Br\u00f8ndby. As his assistant coach, he paired up with former Danish championship winning manager [[John Jensen]], who had played alongside him in the Denmark national team. At the start of his reign, he proclaimed a tactical scheme close to that which Olsen and he had coached at the national team. He renovated the Br\u00f8ndby team by letting a large contingent of older and experienced players leave, in favour of several new offensive players, and he also gave the chance to young talents from the club's youth scheme.\n\n[[File:Michael Laudrup, 2005.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Laudrup as [[Br\u00f8ndby IF|Br\u00f8ndby]] manager]]\n\nTo ensure the defensive strength of the team, Laudrup signed proven national team player [[Morten Wieghorst]]. He began his reign as Br\u00f8ndby manager by winning his first trophy in his managerial career, the 2002 [[Danish Supercup]]. In his first season as head coach, he guided the team to win the [[2002\u201303 Danish Cup|Danish Cup]], after Br\u00f8ndby beat [[FC Midtjylland|Midtjylland]] 3\u20130 in the final and runners-up in the [[2002\u201303 Danish Superliga|Danish Superliga]]. Laudrup's success led him to being voted and awarded the Danish Manager of the Year.\n\nIn the [[2003\u201304 Danish Superliga|following season]], he again finished the season runners-up to first place [[F.C. Copenhagen|Copenhagen]] by just one point. However, he would not be denied in the [[2004-05 in Danish football|2004\u201305 season]], where he finally led the team to the [[2004\u201305 Danish Superliga|Danish Superliga]] title. In the same season, he also completed [[Double (association football)|The Double]] after he won his second [[2004\u201305 Danish Cup|Danish Cup]] in four seasons. This saw him being given his second Danish Manager of the Year award. After finishing runners-up in the [[2005\u201306 Danish Superliga]], Laudrup announced that he, along with assistant Faxe Jensen, could not come to an agreement for a one-year contract extension that was offered by the club. The pair, after winning four trophies in four seasons, subsequently left Br\u00f8ndby in June 2006.<ref>[http://origin.foxsports.news.com.au/story/0,8659,19225470-23210,00.html Laudrup leaving Brondby], [[Fox Sports (USA)|Fox Sports]], 22 May 2006</ref>\n\nLaudrup was associated with several new jobs, including becoming manager of former club Real Madrid and that he would replace [[Lars Lagerb\u00e4ck]] as head coach of the [[Sweden national football team|Sweden national team]].\n\nIn 2007, Br\u00f8ndby decided to name a new lounge at the stadium \"The Michael Laudrup Lounge\", with Laudrup's approval. His success led him to being voted and awarded the Danish Manager of the Year.\n\n===Getafe===\nOn 21 June 2007, Laudrup was linked to a move to [[Madrid]]-based La Liga club [[Getafe CF|Getafe]] by sports newspaper ''Marca''. This was confirmed on 9 July 2007. During his stay in Getafe, the club reached the [[2008 Copa del Rey Final|final]] of the [[Copa del Rey]], losing to [[Valencia CF|Valencia]], and the quarter-finals of the [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]], losing in extra time to [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]]. During his tenure as successor to [[Bernd Schuster]], he brought in a new brand of exciting and free-flowing attacking football to the club, bringing back memories of Laudrup as a player. His team, which was not one of the established powers in Spanish football, enjoyed comparative success. However, he performed only one season as manager, resigning in May 2008.<ref name=\"laudrupleavesgetafe\">{{cite news|work=[[Politiken]]|language=Danish|date=16 May 2008|accessdate=17 May 2008|url=http://politiken.dk/fodbold/article509942.ece|title=Laudrup: Jeg stopper i Getafe|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517035743/http://politiken.dk/fodbold/article509942.ece|archivedate=17 May 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAfter Laudrup announced his departure from Getafe, he was linked with jobs at Barcelona,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fourfourtwo.com/au/news/getafe-owner-reveals-barcelona-wanted-laudrup-guardiola |title=Getafe owner reveals Barcelona wanted Laudrup before Guardiola |work=FourFourTwo.com.au |date=28 October 2013 |accessdate=12 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512232348/http://www.fourfourtwo.com/au/news/getafe-owner-reveals-barcelona-wanted-laudrup-guardiola |archive-date=12 May 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Valencia, [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]], [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]], [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]], [[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]], [[PFC CSKA Moscow|CSKA Moscow]] and [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]. He almost got the job at Panathinaikos, but according to Danish media, he wanted an option to allow him to leave if he received an offer from a Spanish club. This request was not accepted by the Greeks, who chose to hire [[Henk ten Cate]] instead.<ref name=\"laudrupandpanathinaikos\">{{cite news|work=[[Politiken]]|language=Danish|date=6 June 2008|accessdate=6 June 2008|url=http://politiken.dk/fodbold/article519842.ece|title=Gr\u00e6kere afviste Laudrups kattelem|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080607121942/http://politiken.dk/fodbold/article519842.ece|archivedate=7 June 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Michael-Laudrup-Nov2008.jpg|thumb|right|Laudrup at a [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] press conference in 2008]]\n\n===Spartak Moscow===\nOn 12 September 2008, it was officially announced that Laudrup had signed a one-and-a-half-year contract to manage [[FC Spartak Moscow|Spartak Moscow]], replacing Stanislav Cherchesov following his dismissal after a string of poor results.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2008/oct/07/spartakmoscow.europeanfootball|title= Spartak turn to Laudrup|work= The Guardian|date= 12 September 2008}}</ref> However, Laudrup started on a poor note, winning just one of his first four league matches. He was subsequently sacked on 15 April 2009, just seven months on the job,<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/european/5164518/Michael-Laudrup-sacked-by-Spartak-Moscow.html Michael Laudrup sacked by Spartak Moscow], The Telegraph, 16 April 2009</ref> in the wake of Spartak's quarter-final 3\u20130 loss to [[FC Dynamo Moscow|Dynamo Moscow]] in the [[Russian Cup (football)|Russian Cup]]. The official statement from Spartak read, \"From this point onwards, head coach Michael Laudrup has been relieved of his responsibilities because of unsatisfactory results.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/story/2009/04/16/sp-laudrup.html|title= Spartak Moscow fires coach Michael Laudrup|publisher= CBC News|date= 16 April 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 October 2009, Spanish media announced Laudrup would be appointed as new manager of Spanish side [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]], replacing the short and unsuccessful run of [[Abel Resino]], following Atl\u00e9tico's 4\u20130 [[2009\u201310 UEFA Champions League group stage#Group D|UEFA Champions League group stage]] defeat to Chelsea. However, Laudrup and Atl\u00e9tico were not able to agree on terms and the deal fell apart. The day after, on 23 October, Resino was sacked and [[Quique S\u00e1nchez Flores]] was appointed as coach as the side's second-choice.\n\n===Mallorca===\nIn July 2010, Laudrup was appointed manager of [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] on a contract lasting until the end of June 2012. In his first season, he kept the struggling Mallorca side from relegation, which was suffering from losing many first team players and who was ejected from the UEFA Europa League due to its poor financial situation. At the beginning of the [[2011\u201312 La Liga|2011\u201312 season]], on 27 September 2011, Laudrup resigned as manager following the firing of his assistant, Erik Larsen. Laudrup cited great frustration with [[Lorenzo Serra Ferrer]], the club's director of football, leading to a bad work climate as the main reason for his resignation.<ref name=\"laudrupandmallorca\">{{cite news|publisher=[[Bold.dk]]|language=Danish|date=27 September 2011|accessdate=27 September 2011|url=http://www.bold.dk/nyt/Laudrup-Uudholdeligt-arbejdsklima |title=Uudholdeligt arbejdsklima}}</ref>\n\n===Swansea City===\nOn 15 June 2012, Laudrup was appointed manager of [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]] on a two-year contract, becoming the first Dane to manage in the [[Premier League]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/michael-laudrup-didnt-visit-swansea-905125|title=Taking a flyer: Swans boss Laudrup took job without visiting the place|date=21 June 2012|work=The Mirror}}</ref> He made several new signings after arriving at [[Liberty Stadium]], including [[Michu]], [[Chico Flores]], [[Pablo Hern\u00e1ndez (footballer, born 1985)|Pablo Hern\u00e1ndez]], [[Jonathan de Guzm\u00e1n]] and [[Ki Sung-yueng]]. His first competitive match as Swansea manager came as an impressive 0\u20135 away win at [[Loftus Road]] against [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Swansea name Laudrup as manager |url=http://www.premierleague.com/en-gb/news/news/swansea-name-laudrup-as-manager.html |publisher=Premier League |date=15 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120616172336/http://www.premierleague.com/en-gb/news/news/swansea-name-laudrup-as-manager.html |archivedate=16 June 2012 }}</ref>\n\nAt Swansea, [[Alan Tate]] said that Laudrup was considered to be the best player in training, despite being 48 years old.<ref>{{cite news|title=Exclusive&nbsp;\u2013 Tate: Laudrup is the best player in training at Swansea|url=http://www.talksport.co.uk/sports-news/football/premier-league/120819/exclusive-tate-laudrup-best-player-training-swansea-178994#oVbQYbgvobGjCLKj.99|publisher=TalkSport|date=19 August 2012|accessdate=20 August 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120822171133/http://www.talksport.co.uk/sports-news/football/premier-league/120819/exclusive-tate-laudrup-best-player-training-swansea-178994#oVbQYbgvobGjCLKj.99|archive-date=22 August 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> He has been commended for his choice of signings, most notably with Michu, who scored 22 goals in 2012 for Swansea after he signed him for a bargain \u20ac2.5&nbsp;million from [[Rayo Vallecano]].<ref>{{cite news|title=The three amigos: Why La Liga imports|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/swansea-transfer-signings-chico-de-1151772|publisher=Mirror Football|date=20 July 2012|accessdate=20 July 2012}}</ref> On 23 January 2013, he led Swansea into their first ever major cup final after defeating reigning European champions [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] 2\u20130 on aggregate over two legs in the [[2012\u201313 Football League Cup#Semi-finals|League Cup semi-finals]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Swansea 0\u20130 Chelsea (2\u20130)|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21038756|publisher=BBC Sport|date=23 January 2013|accessdate=24 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 February 2013, Laudrup appointed former Danish international midfielder [[Morten Wieghorst]] as his assistant after previously signing him as a player when Laudrup was managing Br\u00f8ndby.<ref>{{cite news|title=Morten Wieghorst appointed to Swansea City role|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21372756|publisher=BBC Sport|date= 7 February 2013|accessdate= 7 February 2013}}</ref> Laudrup would later say he \"certainly\" believes Wieghorst \"can be manager\" of Swansea, as \"he has experience from Scottish football and is familiar with English football\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Morten Wieghorst could be next Swansea City manager&nbsp;\u2013 Laudrup|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11731/8520351/Morten-Wieghorst-could-be-next-Swansea-City-manager-according-to-Michael-Laudrup|publisher=Sky Sports|date= 23 February 2013|accessdate= 23 February 2013}}</ref> On 24 February, Laudrup said he had no \"ambition to become the manager\" of a big club, because he could not \"have done everything for 10 years\" in management and then be fired \"after nine months\" for not winning any trophies.<ref>{{cite news|title=Michael Laudrup says no to Chelsea and Real Madrid|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/fa-league-cups/michael-laudrup-says-no-to-chelsea-and-real-madrid-8508298.html|work=The Independent|date= 24 February 2013|accessdate= 24 February 2013|location=London|first=Steve|last=Tongue}}</ref> He also said it gave him \"much more pleasure to see how well\" he could do where he did not \"have to win all the time\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Laudrup: I'm not desperate to manage a bigger club|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11731/8521157/Michael-Laudrup-I-m-not-desperate-to-manage-a-bigger-club-than-Swansea |publisher=Sky Sports|date= 24 February 2013|accessdate= 24 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 February 2013, Laudrup won his first trophy with Swansea after his side beat [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] 5\u20130 to [[2013 Football League Cup Final|win]] the [[Football League Cup]] at [[Wembley stadium|Wembley]].<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/feb/24/nathan-dyer-swansea-bradford-capital-one|title= Nathan Dyer double helps Swansea ruin Bradford's Capital One Cup dream|date=25 February 2013|work=Guardian UK|accessdate=26 February 2013|location=London|first=Andy|last=Hunter}}</ref> This was also Swansea's first major trophy in English football in the club's history. After the match, he said, \"I'm very proud of my team today. I think it was a great performance.\" He also hailed the win as the best in his managerial career, saying, \"As a manager it's absolutely at the top, winning a trophy for the first time in 100 years.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Laudrup hails greatest managerial achievement|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2283833/Michael-Laudrup-delighted-Swansea-beat-Bradford-League-Cup-final-Wembley.html |work=Daily Mail|date= 24 February 2013|accessdate= 24 February 2013|location=London}}</ref>\n\nFollowing Swansea's 1\u20130 win over [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] on 2 March 2013<ref>{{cite news|title=Swansea 1\u20130 Newcastle&nbsp;\u2013 Report |url = http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/261838/report |publisher=BBC Sport|date= 2 March 2013|accessdate= 2 March 2013}}</ref> the club moved into eighth position in the top-half of the Premier League table, seemingly safe from relegation with 40 points and ten games left; Laudrup said he wanted Swansea to finish eighth, stating that \"coming eighth [will be] like winning the league\" for the club because he felt \"the first seven spots\" were already taken by [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]], Chelsea, [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]], [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] and [[Everton F.C.|Everton]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Swansea boss Michael Laudrup eyes 'incredible' league finish |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21647601 |publisher=BBC Sport|date= 3 March 2013|accessdate= 3 March 2013}}</ref> On 3 March, though he had said that his \"intention\" was \"to stay\" in south Wales for the next year, Swansea chairman Huw Jenkins said that the club were in the \"process of looking for the next manager\" of the club in case Laudrup did choose to leave the club.<ref>{{cite news|title=Swansea chairman Huw Jenkins preparing for life after Michael Laudrup |url = http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11731/8537426/Swansea-chairman-Huw-Jenkins-preparing-for-life-after-Michael-Laudrup |publisher=Sky Sports|date= 3 March 2013|accessdate= 3 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 March 2013, Laudrup signed a new contract with Swansea, keeping him at the club until 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=Michael Laudrup signs fresh Swansea deal |url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21719120 |publisher=BBC Sport|date= 8 March 2013|accessdate= 8 March 2013}}</ref> Reports indicated that he agreed to a contract with a release clause in the region of \u00a35&nbsp;million, much like the release clause [[Brendan Rodgers]] agreed to when he signed a contract extension at the Liberty Stadium four months prior to joining Liverpool.<ref>{{cite news|title=Danish delight for Swansea as Laudrup signs one-year contract extension |url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2290309/Michael-Laudrup-signs-year-contract-extension-Swansea.html |work=Daily Mail|date= 8 March 2013|accessdate= 8 March 2013|location=London|first=Riath|last=Al-Samarrai}}</ref> On 10 May, however, he confirmed that his \"intention\" was to stay at Swansea \"next season,\" saying that reports he wanted to leave Wales was \"pure speculation.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Swansea manager Michael Laudrup dismisses Everton speculation |url = http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11661/8703459/Swansea-manager-Michael-Laudrup-dismisses-Everton-speculation |publisher=SkySports|date= 10 May 2013|accessdate= 10 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 February 2014, Laudrup was sacked by Swansea following a poor run of form which left the club two points clear of relegation.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2551760/Michael-Laudrup-sacked-Dane-parts-company-Swansea-talks-chairman-Jenkins.html|title=Laudrup sacked! Dane leaves Swansea after crisis meeting with chairman Jenkins|date=4 February 2014|work=Daily Mail|accessdate=5 February 2014}}</ref> At the time of the decision, the team had lost six out of their last eight league games.<ref name=\"BBC Sport\"/>\n\n===Lekhwiya===\nOn 30 June 2014, Laudrup became the new manager of [[Qatar Stars League]] champions [[Lekhwiya SC|Lekhwiya]] after signing a one-year deal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Michael Laudrup to coach the Qatari champions|url=http://www.qsl.com.qa/users/newsen/NewsDetails.aspx?pid=2244|publisher=Qatar Stars League|date=1 July 2014|accessdate=1 July 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714162401/http://www.qsl.com.qa/users/newsen/NewsDetails.aspx?pid=2244|archivedate=14 July 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He guided the Lekhwiya to a club-record Qatar Stars League and a [[Qatar Crown Prince Cup|Crown Prince Cup]] double in his first season. The club also qualified for the quarter-finals of the [[2015 AFC Champions League]] during his reign. On 17 June 2015, Laudrup announced that he would not extend his contract, departing the club.<ref>{{cite news|title= Michael Laudrup f\u00e6rdig i Qatar |url = http://www.dr.dk/Sporten/Fodbold/2015/06/17/0617161946.htm |publisher=Danmarks Radio |date=17 June 2015|accessdate=17 June 2015|language=da}}</ref>\n\n===Al Rayyan===\nOn 3 October 2016, Laudrup was unveiled as the new manager of [[Al-Rayyan SC|Al Rayyan]] on a two-year contract, replacing [[Jorge Fossati]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Michael Laudrup unveiled as Al Rayyan coach |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/michael-laudrup-unveiled-al-rayyan-coach-152731965--sow.html |website=[[Yahoo! Sports]] |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |date=3 October 2016 |accessdate=21 October 2016}}</ref> His first match in charge was on 15 October 2016, when Al Rayyan faced [[Al-Sailiya SC|Al Sailiya]] in an away match in the league, with the match ending in a 1\u20131 draw.<ref>{{cite news |script-title=ar:\u0627\u0644\u0631\u064a\u0627\u0646 \u064a\u062a\u0639\u0627\u062f\u0644 \u0645\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u064a\u0644\u064a\u0629 \u0628\u0647\u062f\u0641 \u0644\u0645\u062b\u0644\u0647 |url=http://www.alrayyansc.com/new/newsdetails.php?id=8161 |website=Al Rayyan SC official website |date=15 October 2016 |accessdate=21 October 2016 |language=Arabic |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161021201902/http://www.alrayyansc.com/new/newsdetails.php?id=8161 |archive-date=21 October 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Tactics==\n{{see also|4-2-3-1}}\nAs assistant manager to [[Morten Olsen]], the Denmark national team employed a [[Formation (association football)|4\u20132\u20133\u20131 system]] with pacey wingers playing the pivotal role in [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|attack]]. Laudrup learnt from Olsen and used the same tactical style with Br\u00f8ndby, with the team becoming more attacking and focused on a short passing style. He continued to employ a similar tactical style when he joined Getafe, ushering a new brand of exciting and free-flowing attacking football to help the club to the Copa del Rey final. However, at Spartak Moscow, he could not adapt his formation and tactics to the Russian game, with the club unable to score enough goals ''per'' match.\n\nAs Mallorca manager, Laudrup inspired a team that lost a number of key players from relegation by playing an offensive game. In 2012, he joined Swansea City as manager, replacing Brendan Rodgers.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://thinkfootball.co.uk/archives/6885 | title = Tactical analysis: How have Swansea evolved under Laudrup? | work = Think Football | date = 14 December 2012 | accessdate = 14 December 2012 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121218015638/http://thinkfootball.co.uk/archives/6885 | archivedate = 18 December 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Under Rodgers, Swansea were known to play a [[Formation (association football)|4\u20133\u20133]] approach with a lot of focus on passing, where the full-backs pushed up when in possession and the outfield players played a high tempo pressing game. Under Laudrup, the team began employing a [[Formation (association football)|4\u20132\u20133\u20131]] formation, becoming more attacking while retaining the passing and pressing game. He also signed a number of new players, primarily from La Liga, trying to bring the attacking style from Spain to Wales, which saw more goals scored.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.just-football.com/2012/12/tactical-analysis-laudrups-swansea-vs-brendan-rodgers-changes/ | title = Tactical Analysis: Laudrup\u2019s Swansea to Brendan Rodgers\u2019? |work=Just Football | date = 19 December 2012 | accessdate = 19 December 2012 }}</ref> He said, \"You can get a lot of quality for a reasonable amount in Spain right now.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.talksport.co.uk/magazine/features/130216/swanseas-michael-laudrup-perfect-manager-chelsea-and-heres-why-191678 |title=Swansea's Michael Laudrup is the perfect manager for Chelsea |work=talkSPORT |date=16 February 2013 |accessdate=16 February 2013 }}{{Dead link|date=April 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nLaudrup earned plaudits for maintaining their flowing, attacking brand of football and attractive, passing style of play throughout the season, which saw his side win the League Cup, after beating Bradford City a record 5\u20130 in the final. \"You can't ask players to do things that [[Cristiano Ronaldo]] and [[Lionel Messi]] are doing, but you can ask the easy things,\" he said. \"Sometimes the easiest things in football, a simple pass five or eight yards, can be the most effective. That, everybody can learn.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espnfc.com/blog/_/name/relegationzone/id/102/michael-laudrups-swansea-style?cc=3888 |title=Michael Laudrup's Swansea style |work=ESPN Blog |date=30 August 2012 |accessdate=30 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nMichael Laudrup is part of a family with three generations of footballers. His uncle is former Br\u00f8ndby and [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] manager [[Ebbe Skovdahl]]. He is the son of former Danish national team player [[Finn Laudrup]] and Michael's oldest son [[Mads Laudrup]] has been the team captain of various Danish youth national teams since January 2005, and his youngest son [[Andreas Laudrup]] was selected a part of the under-16 national team in March 2006.<ref>Thomas M\u00f8ller Johansen, \"Laudrup d. V\", ''[[B.T. (tabloid)|BT]] article'', 11 March 2006</ref>\n\nMichael Laudrup has a younger brother, [[Brian Laudrup]], who was also a footballer. Brian Laudrup is the record holder of Danish player of the year awards with four,<ref>{{in lang|da}} [http://politiken.dk/sport/fodbold/ECE1810723/naturlig-anfoerer-vinder-titlen-som-aarets-danske-fodboldspiller/ \u00bbNaturlig anf\u00f8rer\u00ab vinder titlen som \u00e5rets danske fodboldspiller]. Politiken.dk (1 January 2012). Retrieved 2015-04-18.</ref> and was rated by FIFA as the fifth-best player in the world in 1992.<ref>[http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/fifa-awards.html FIFA Awards] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160112042845/http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/fifa-awards.html |date=12 January 2016 }}. Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation.com (12 February 2015). Retrieved 2015-04-18.</ref> Brian Laudrup was in the Euro 92 Team of the Tournament and World Cup 98 Team of the Tournament. Brian was also known for his part in the [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] squad which won nine consecutive titles in the 1990s. Brian was a part of the trophy-winning Danish national team at [[UEFA Euro 1992]], but Michael did not play in that championship due to differences with the national team coach [[Richard M\u00f8ller Nielsen]]<ref>[[#Kvist|Kvist]] (2001), p. 155</ref> and because he thought that the barring of Yugoslavia for political, rather than football, reasons was not just.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.arhiva.serbia.gov.rs/news/2000-07/04/19747.html|publisher=Post Festum|title=Yugoslavia vs. Spain&nbsp;\u2013 the best match}}</ref> In 2004, both the Laudrup brothers were named in the [[FIFA 100]], a list of the 125 greatest living footballers chosen by [[Pel\u00e9]] as part of the celebration of [[FIFA]]'s 100th anniversary.\n\nLaudrup is married to Siw Retz Laudrup. But with his ex-wife Tina Thun\u00f8, he had his elder son, [[Mads Laudrup|Mads]]. With his wife Siw Retz Laudrup, he has two children, [[Andreas Laudrup|Andreas]] and Rebecca.<ref>{{cite news|title=Michael Laudrup's daughter Rebecca gives thumbs up to Swansea shopping |url=http://www.thisissouthwales.co.uk/Michael-Laudrup-s-daughter-Rebecca-gives-thumbs/story-16433681-detail/story.html |publisher=South Wales|date= 22 June 2012|accessdate= 22 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Politics and business==\nAlongside his professional football career, Laudrup began importing Spanish wine to Denmark starting in 1993. Initially, the wine import was sort of a hobby, but business grew rapidly and today his company Laudrup Vin og Gastronomi has over ten employees, runs a Wine Academy and imports wines from all over the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laudrup.dk/infopages/historie_profil.asp|title=Historien bag Laudrup Vin \u2013 salg af kvalitetsvin siden 1993|website=laudrup.dk|access-date=20 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070315102734/http://www.laudrup.dk/infopages/historie_profil.asp|archive-date=15 March 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Michael Laudrup was one of the founders of [[CEPOS]], a Danish classical liberal/free-market conservative think-tank.<ref>{{cite news|title=Founders|url=https://www.cepos.dk/om-cepos/personer-tilknyttet-cepos/stiftere/|publisher=CEPOs|language=Danish|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140214181547/http://www.cepos.dk/om-cepos/personer-tilknyttet-cepos/stiftere|archivedate=14 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Club performance\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | Cup\n! colspan=2 | League Cup\n! colspan=2 | Continental\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n! Season\n! Club\n! League\n! Apps || Goals\n! Apps || Goals\n! Apps || Goals\n! Apps || Goals\n! Apps || Goals\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Denmark\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | [[Danish Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | League Cup\n! colspan=2 | [[UEFA|Europe]]\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n|1981||[[Kj\u00f8benhavns Boldklub|KB]]||[[Danish 1st Division|1st Division]]||14||3||||||colspan=2|-||2||0||16||3\n|-\n|1982||rowspan=2|[[Br\u00f8ndby IF|Br\u00f8ndby]]||rowspan=2|[[Danish 1st Division|