{"title_page": "List of spacecraft with electric propulsion", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Update|inaccurate=yes|date=April 2020}}\nIn chronological order, spacecrafts are listed equipped with [[Electrically powered spacecraft propulsion|electric space propulsion]]. This includes both cruise engines and/or thrusters for attitude and orbit control. It is not specified whether the given engine is the sole means of propulsion or whether other types of engine are also used on a spacecraft. The list does not claim to be comprehensive.\n\n==Chronological overview==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width: 100%;\"\n|+ Spacecraft with electric propulsion\n! Spacecraft name \n! Launch date \n! End of life \n! Thruster type\n! class=\"unsortable\"|No. \n! Model \n! Propellant\n! colspan=\"2\"|Spacecraft customer\n! colspan=\"2\"|Thruster prime\n! Comment \n|- ----\n| Program 661A Flight A || {{dts|18-12-1962|abbr=on}} || {{dts|18-12-1962|abbr=on}} || [[Ion Engine|Ion engine]] || 1 ||  || Cesium || {{flagicon|United States}} || USAF || {{flagicon|United States}} ||EOS (Electro-Optical Systems, Inc.) || Suborbital, no operation of on-board ion engine\n|- ----\n|[[Kosmos 21]] || {{dts|11-11-1963|abbr=on}} || {{dts|11-11-1963|abbr=on}} || [[Pulsed plasma thruster]] || || || [[Polytetrafluoroethylene|PTFE]]   || {{flagicon|USSR}} ||  || {{flagicon|USSR}} ||[[Kurchatov Institute]]/[[OKB-1]] || Launch failure\n|- ----\n| [[SERT-1|SERT 1]] || {{dts|20-07-1964|abbr=on}} || {{dts|20-07-1964|abbr=on}} || Ion engine || 1<br /> 1 ||  || Mercury<br /> Cesium || {{flagicon|United States}} || NASA || {{flagicon|United States}} ||NASA<br /> Hughes || ''Space Electric Rocket Test'', suborbital (31 min), the first demonstration of an ion engine in space - only the mercury engine by NASA was operated\n|- ----\n| Program 661A Flight B || {{dts|29-08-1964|abbr=on}} || {{dts|29-08-1964|abbr=on}} || Ion engine || 1 || || Cesium || {{flagicon|United States}} || U